    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4ad7c8d0-60a9-4489-afaa-60f2813d9d52",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 39-year-old man in the Czech Republic who comes in looking tired and worried after several weeks of poor appetite because stomach pain makes it hard for him to eat and he feels full immediately after starting meals [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6]. He also reports a painful lump under the left nipple, about the size of a quarter, which has been present for a few weeks and hurts when touched [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6].\n\nHe says the abdominal pain has begun to interfere with his daily routine because he avoids food to prevent the pain and early fullness [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6]. He has also had cough and intermittent fever, and the need for chest imaging is consistent with concern for pulmonary infection such as pneumonia in a patient with infection-related respiratory symptoms [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:0, MEDDIALOG:B20.0:2].\n\n{patientName} works a steady office-based job and lives independently; outside work he prefers quiet evenings at home and meeting a small circle of friends on weekends. He is normally private and self-reliant, but the combination of chest symptoms, poor eating, and the breast-area lump has made him seek care sooner than usual [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6].\n\nHe has no dramatic external distress on first meeting, but his reduced oral intake and anxious focus on the painful nipple lump are prominent. He is especially concerned because the pain with eating and rapid fullness have continued rather than improving on their own [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:980bc832-ab2b-421a-98cd-170a2934f6c2",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has HIV infection with current illness concerning for mycobacterial coinfection, based on cough, intermittent fever, and the need for chest imaging to assess infectious lung disease [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:0, MEDDIALOG:B20.0:2]. Over the last few weeks he has developed a painful lump under the left nipple and significant stomach pain with immediate fullness after eating, which has reduced his food intake [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6].\n\nHe denies any major traumatic explanation for the breast-area complaint and describes the lump as tender to touch [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6]. Prior clinicians advised that a lump under the nipple should be removed and biopsied for diagnosis [MEDDIALOG:B20.0:6]. He has no additional documented chronic comorbidities in the provided evidence, so the remainder of his past history is unremarkable by report."
          }
        ]
      }
